1. Indroduction

Inertial navigation system (INS) [1] , [2] is an essential navigation component of many carriers such as aircraft and ships because of its independence. However, the error of INS will accumulate gradually, resulting in the decline of the navigation accuracy over time. The rotational inertial navigation system (RINS) offsets the influence of constant and slowly varying gyro drift and accelerometer bias by periodically rotating the inertial measurement unit (IMU) composed of gyros and accelerometers [3] , which improve the positioning accuracy of INS. However, due to the influence of unmodulable gyro drift and angle random walk [4] , the navigation accuracy will still decline with time. The error of GPS does not diverge with time, so the integration of GPS and RINS [5] , [6] can effectively improve the navigation accuracy for a long time.

In integrated navigation system, GPS positioning accuracy is affected by many factors, such as clock error, ionosphere error, multipath effect and so on, which has a key impact on navigation accuracy [7] . In addition, the signal strength of GPS is low and its transmission frequency and the signal structure of C/A code are public. Therefore it may also be subject to malicious electromagnetic interference , including signal jamming [8] and signal spoofing. In signal spoofing, the false signal is provided to the receiver to induce the receiver to use the false signal for positioning calculation, so that the positioning result obtained by the GPS receiver deviates from the real value. GPS spoofing can be divided into forwarding spoofing and generative spoofing. In the forward spoofing, it mainly includes a GPS receiver and a signal transmitter. After receiving the real GPS satellite signal, the pseudo range measurement value is changed by adding delay. Then, the spoofing signal is forwarded to the target receiver after increasing the power, so as to achieve the effect of positioning deception [9] . In the generative spoofing, the spoofing receiver synchronizes with the real satellite signal, estimates the signal parameters of each visible star tracked by the target receiver, mainly including Doppler offset and phase of C/A code, and then generates the corresponding deception signal based on the velocity information and position of the target receiver [10] .

In order to mitigate the influence of GPS spoofing, different types of anti-spoofing techniques have been studied [11] , [12] , [13] , [14] which can be divided into three levels. The first one is based on the detection of GPS signal, including signal power detection, signal quality monitoring (SQM), residual signal detection and so on [15] . The second level is the consistency check of GPS data, such as clock consistency check, receiving ephemeris consistency check, etc. [16] . The third level is the detection of navigation and positioning. The main method is the Receiver Autonomous Integrity Monitoring (RAIM) [17] , which uses redundant satellite data to detect GPS integrity, such as the parity space method based on fault detection and isolation (FDI) [18] , [19] .

In addition, GPS spoofing can also be detected with the help of other navigation and positioning devices. In the GPS/INS integrated navigation system, the data of INS can be used as redundant information to detect GPS spoofing [20] , [21] . A batch least squares residuals is described to detect GPS spoofing attacks in [22] and a batch implementation of tightly coupled GPS/INS is provided. The simulation results show that the integrity risk meets the requirements during the 8 min simulation. However, the probability of misdetection will increase if the trajectory is measured by the attacker. In addition, the computational burden is also a limitation of this method. C. Tanil et al. [23] proposed an innovation-based spoofing monitor and integrated it into the Kalman filter of tightly coupled GNSS/INS integration. An evaluation model based on Kalman filter is derived to evaluate the performance of INS monitor. The simulation results show that, The rate of misdetection under the error of 10 m remains below 10 -9 during 280 s landing approach of B747. The monitor is also applied in loosely coupled integration and proved to be effective in the simulation of 200 s [24] . In addition, the simulation also shows that the loosely coupled integration has better resistance, because it is easier to introduce the GPS spoofing into the filter in the tightly coupled integration, which will lead to the error of IMU biases estimation.

The above studies focus on the detection ability of spoofing in the short term and lack of treatment for long-term spoofing. And the integrity risk increases with the time of spoofing. Under slow and long-time spoofing, the wrong data will affect the estimation of the filter, resulting in detection failure and filter divergence. The sensitivity of the above methods to slow spoofing and the resistance to long-term spoofing need to be improved.

This paper proposes an anti-spoofing integrated navigation method for the integration of GPS and INS/RINS. In the process of integrated navigation, GPS spoofing is detected according to the positioning results of INS and the prediction position information given in the time update process of Kalman filter (KF). When the GPS positioning result passes the spoofing detection, the measurement update process is executed. The main contribution of this paper is to propose a new detection strategy, which can improve the sensitivity to errors, and provide the strategy of the filter under spoofing, which can reduce the impact of error data on the estimation results and maintain the monitoring of spoofing for a long time. Meanwhile, this method does not require any modification to the existing GPS receiver or addition of other equipment.

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. The Section 2 describes the configuration of RINS and the definition of coordinate. In Section 3 , a GPS spoofing detection method based on INS and prediction results of KF is proposed. In Section 4 , the proposed method is verified by simulation, and a vehicular experiment is carried out to verify the effectiveness of the method in Section 5 . The Section 6 draws a conclusion.
2. Description of INS and definition of coordinate

Firstly, the definitions of INS and coordinate frames are described. The core component of the RINS is the IMU which is composed of three gyroscopes and three accelerometers. In RINS, the IMU is installed in the chassis through the frame structure. Taking a dual-axis RINS as an example, the IMU is installed in the chassis by two frame structures as shown in Fig. 1 . The IMU is fixed in the inner frame, one side of the inner frame and the outer frame is equipped with a servo motor to drive the frame to rotate, and the other side of the frame is equipped with a grating encoder to measure the rotation angle of the frame.

