Take the latitude error δ L as an example. Due to the obvious modulation effect of the dual-axis RINS on horizontal drifts and biases, ε E and ∇ N as residual errors can be relatively ignored, and can be simplified to (4) δ L = δ L 0 + ϕ E 0 - ϕ E 0 C s + ϕ U 0 c o s L ω i e ω s + δ V N 0 V I S s = A + B · c o s ω s t + C · s i n ω s t

In, δ L 0 , ϕ E 0 , ϕ U 0 , ω s , δ V N 0 , V I are constant values. Since ω ie is a relatively small quantity, ω ie cos L can be expanded at the current position and regarded as a constant value after taking the first-order Taylor expansion . Therefore, the latitude error caused by the RINS can be regarded as a constant term and sine-cosine term in a short time. In the integrated navigation, the latitude error is calculated by the latitude difference between RINS and GPS, which can be written as follows (5) δ L = L INS - L GPS where L INS is the latitude calculated by the RINS and L GPS is the latitude given by GPS. Due to the error propagation characteristics of inertial navigation, the error in L INS will have a trend term as, while the error of GPS in L GPS under normal conditions is reflected in the form of noise. When GPS is spoofed, δ L will not conform to the law described by the inertial navigation error propagation equation, so spoofing may be detected. It can be considered that the trend term of δ L is related to RINS, and the noise term is related to the positioning accuracy of GPS. When GPS is not deceived, the trend term of δ L is regular. Therefore, the position error at t k can be predicted through the position error between 0 t ̃ k - 1 . Generally, the value of t k - 1 should be greater than 1/4 Schuler period as (4) contains the cosine term of Schuler period.

