The latitude error at t k can be predicted by as follows (8) δ L ̂ k / k - 1 = f ̂ k - 1 t k + σ L where σ L is the positioning noise of GPS. Thus, an appropriate threshold T L can be designed according to σ L . When the latitude error δ L measured according is within the range of δ L ̂ k / k - 1 - T L , δ L ̂ k / k - 1 + T L , the result of GPS receiver is considered to be effective, otherwise it is considered to be spoofed. Similarly, an appropriate threshold T λ can be set for the longitude range to judge the effectiveness of GPS.
3.2. Judge according to the prediction error of KF

In GPS /RINS integration, a Kalman filter [21] is generally used for optimal estimation. If the state equation and measurement equation corresponding to KF are as follows (9) X k = Φ k , k - 1 X k - 1 + W k - 1 Z k = H k X k + V k

The state X k is set according to the errors of RINS and GPS in the integration. In this paper, the following state quantities are set (10) X = δ λ , δ L , δ V E , δ V N , ϕ E , ϕ N , ϕ U , ε x , ε y , ε z , ∇ x , ∇ y , ∇ z T where the subscripts x , y , z indicate that the state variable is represented in the s-frame. The state transition matrix Φ k , k - 1 is obtained by discretizing the state transition matrix of the differential equation of inertial navigation errors [20] , and the variance matrix Q of system excitation noise W k - 1 is determined by the noise characteristics of the RINS.

The measurement Z k is the error between RINS and GPS at time k. In this paper, the position error is selected as the measurement, which can be written as the follows (11) Z = λ RINS - λ GPS , L RINS - L GPS T

At this time, the variance matrix R k of the measurement noise V k is the positioning noise when GPS is in normal state.

